es and a more mystical one about his self-sacrifice on the world-tree in order to gain magical wisdom; V&#x01EB;lundarkviða, which recounts an elvish smith’s revenge for his captivity and maiming; and Hervararkviða, where the heroine bravely but foolishly raises her dead father to demand the deadly sword Tyrfingr from him.Originally published between 1988 and 2008, these twelve essays cover a wide range of mythological and heroic poems and have been revised and updated to reflect the latest scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEddasxHistory and criticism. 0aMythology, Norse, in literature. 0aOld Norse poetryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aKick, Donata , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShafer, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266926040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442669260423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442669260.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK